#Text=CHAPTER SIXTEEN

#Text=The two girls let themselves into the house noiselessly , and , turning out the hall-light , left for them by their mother , crept upstairs on tiptoe ; and went through the upper hall directly to Laura 's room -- Cora 's being nearer the sick-room .
#Text=At their age it is proper that a gayety be used three times : in anticipation , and actually , and in after-rehearsal .
#Text=The last was of course now in order : they went to Laura 's room to " talk it over . "
#Text=There was no gas-fixture in this small chamber ; but they found Laura 's oil-lamp burning brightly upon her writing-table .
#Text=" How queer ! " said Laura with some surprise , as she closed the door .
#Text=" Mother never leaves the lamp lit for me ; she 's always so afraid of lamps exploding . "
#Text=" Perhaps Miss Peirce came in here to read , and forgot to turn it out , " suggested Cora , seating herself on the edge of the bed and letting her silk wrap fall from her shoulders .
#Text=" Oh , Laura , was n't he gorgeous . . . . "

#Text=She referred to the gallant defender of our seas , it appeared , and while Laura undressed and got into a wrapper , Cora recounted in detail the history of the impetuous sailor 's enthrallment ; -- a resume predicted three hours earlier by a gleeful whisper hissed across the maritime shoulder as the sisters swung near each other during a waltz :
#Text=" proposed ! "
#Text=" I 've always heard they 're horribly inconstant , " she said , regretfully .
#Text=" But , oh , Laura , was n't he beautiful to look at !
#Text=They ought to all wear ' em .
#Text=It would look silly on such a little goat as that Wade Trumble , though : nothing could make him look like a whole man .
#Text=Did you see him glaring at me ?
#Text=Beast !
#Text=I was going to be so nice and kittenish and do all my prettiest tricks for him , to help Val with his oil company .
#Text=Val thinks Wade would come in yet , if I'D only get him in the mood to have another talk with Val about it ; but the spiteful little rat would n't come near me .
#Text=I believe that was one of the reasons Val laughed at me and pretended not to mind my getting proposed to .
#Text=He must have minded ; he could n't have helped minding it , really .
#Text=That 's his way ; he 's so mean -- he wo n't show things .
#Text=He knows me .
#Text=I ca n't keep anything from him ; he reads me like a signboard ; and then about himself he keeps me guessing , and I ca n't tell when I 've guessed right .
#Text=Ray Vilas behaved disgustingly , of course ; he was horrid and awful .
#Text=I might have expected it .
#Text=I suppose Richard was wailing his tiresome sorrows on your poor shoulder -- -- "
#Text=" He was very cheerful .

#Text= It must be after three , " she said , listlessly , having gone over her evening so often that the colours were beginning to fade .

column1: #Text=She yawned again .
#Text=" Laura , " she remarked absently , " I do n't see how you can sleep in this bed ; it sags so . "
#Text=" I 've never noticed it , " said her sister .
#Text=" It 's a very comfortable old bed . "
#Text=Cora went to her to be unfastened , reverting to the lieutenant during the operation , and kissing the tire-woman warmly at its conclusion .
#Text=" You 're always so sweet to me , Laura , " she said affectionately .
#Text=" I do n't know how you manage it .
#Text="sometimes I wonder how you stand me .
